{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"388b2270-119f-4b45-8574-8e1d1fb8dd1d","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports the modern approach. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    // TestContext is injected automatically via constructor in MSTest 3.x\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous init here (e.g., create objects, set fields)\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // Async init here (e.g., seed a database, call an API)\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void SyncTest() { /* ... */ }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task AsyncTest() { /* ... */ }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for MSTest 3.x:**\n\n- **Constructor injection** — `TestContext` is passed via the constructor (no need for the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property-setter pattern).\n- **Sync init** — put it in the constructor.\n- **Async init** — use `[TestInitialize]` with an `async Task` method, since constructors can't be async.\n- **Cleanup** — similarly, use `[TestCleanup]` (supports `async Task`) or implement `IAsyncDisposable`/`IDisposable`.\n\nWant me to scaffold a test file in your project?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"74de44ff-b29d-4142-8320-65df1f3aeaae","outputTokens":353,"requestId":"67D2:228EC1:2D220DA:31C7625:69FD3F80"},"id":"a351099d-6131-466e-b6cc-0d515967e07e","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:42:34.822Z","parentId":"f6888f31-065e-49ff-859c-0909de51e3b3"}
